<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-06-11T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-06-11T22:00:00-05:00" n="400" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d400">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">693.001/553: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dooman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-06-12T12:00:00+09:00">June 12,
                                    1939—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received June 12—6:40 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>268. Department’s 137, May 20, 3 p.m., via Shanghai, North China trade
                            restrictions.</p>
                        <p>The British Embassy presented a note to the Foreign Office on June 9. We
                            presented a note along the lines indicated today.<note n="72" xml:id="d400fn72">
                                <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_848">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol.
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 848</ref>.</note>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Dooman</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>